e Lackington statement of account (written out for PBS at a single sitting) was is in error and that the account was debited not on 3 November 1817 but on 3 January 1818, the day after PBS repeated his request for "ten additional copies."}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri55\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  35.\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri55\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart33\pnindent528\pnf2{\pntxta .}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 I have not been able to confirm that this review was in fact published in March: the earliest advertisement announcing the contents of the March \i Edinburgh Magazine \i0 that I have encountered is in the \i Morning Chronicle \i0 of 9 April (page 2, column 1), but such advertisements frequently appeared days or weeks after a magazine was published. I have no information on the publication date of the March \i La Belle Assemblee.}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri62\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  36.\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri62\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart33\pnindent528\pnf2{\pntxta .}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 For these dates, see the preliminary "To Correspondents" section in \i Blackwood's, 2 \i0 (February 1818). To confirm the latter date, see the advertisement for the March \i Blackwood's \i0 in the \i Morning Chronicle, \i0 31 March 1818 (page 2, column 1).}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri53\sb5\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  37.\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri53\sb5\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart33\pnindent528\pnf2{\pntxta .}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 These late advertisements prove that Lackington still had an interest in the novel, and they therefore call into question the 22 May 1818 "Dateof Issue" that is given for \i Frankenstein \i0 in a handwritten Colburn "list of publications." \i Frankenstein \i0 seems to have been entered into the 1818" lists " as a consequence of Colburn having "published" an edition of \i Frankenstein \i0 on 4 April 1826 (see Chronology for that date as well as Bentley Archives, University of Illinois Library, microfilm reel #10). It is possible, however, that Colburn on 22 May 1818 purchased at discount 25 or more of the remaining copies from Lackington in order to sell them from his own shop.}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li504\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  38.\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\ql\li504\fi0\ri0\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart33\pnindent528\pnf2{\pntxta .}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 For the redating of this letter in PBS \i Letters \i0 from 18 to 19 August, see \i SC, \i0 VI, \i 679, \i0 n.ll.}\par {\pntext\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri38\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20  39.\tab}\pard \plain \cbpat8\qj\li5\fi499\ri38\sb0\sa0\sl-259\slmult0\tx1032 \f2\fs20{\*\pn\pnlvlbody\pndec\pnstart33\pnindent528\pnf2{\pntxta .}}\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 {\b0\i0\cf1\charscalex100\expndtw0\dn0\f2\cchs0\lang1033\langfe1033\fs20 For Godwin's response and letters, see \i SC